== What are we working on? ==

It~is definitely right  if  you are~thinking of~Luwrain primarily 
as~of~a~special conception for~interaction for~blind people with~personal computers.
This~approach, which we~called "text-based interface", in~conjunction with~technologies 
chosen for~implementation, gives really new~chances to~improve lifes of~handicapped people.
Arguably, the~navigation over a~text file 
is the~most comfortable and understandable way of~doing anything on PC's with~assistive technologies
and Luwrain's idea is to~spread this simple finding everywhere.
That doesn't mean that Luwrain hasn't any elements similar to~GUI items at all totally 
(e.g. forms or menus) 
but all of them should be reconsidered in~new~way. 
Just imagine:

* No~potentially inaccessible objects in~working area, 
user is always  sure that there is nothing unknown to him/her

* Every object can be explored letter-by-letter quickly and easily

* In~any place  user can do a~search for~a~particular  substring 
regardless what structure the~current object has,
whether it is a~file~manager panel, a~message~composer, an~address book entry or a~media player control

* Any~fragment of~working space can be~copied to~clipboard and pasted as~text,
say, for~sending as~a~message to~friend

Do~not~suspect Luwrain of~being one~more sophisticated text editor, it~is~not the~case.
Luwrain offers the~text navigation only just  as~some sort of~logical level,
there can be as~complex structure behind it as~you want.
In~contrast to~GNU~Emacs 
(which could be fairly considered as~an~origin of~inspiration for~us) 
Luwrain doesn't store the~real text as~a~single solid buffer.

The~Luwrain environment tries to~develop proposed text-based approach 
making it really complete and useful.
User navigation commands are announced with~special comments 
describing what he/she has under the~current cursor position.
All~object are~gathered  in~applications 
which user is~able to~launch as~many as~his/her computer can.
Their standard set includes file~manager, 
media player, 
text~editor with~office documents filters,
mail client,
news reader,
personal address book and scheduler,
command line terminal etc.

== Hm, what can we do with that? ==

The~idea suggested above is~implemented using Java.
That makes Luwrain potentially available on~any~operating system which has a~proper Java~SE support.
It is true enough but Luwrain shows its best primarily on~GNU/Linux,
which it has been initially designed for.
The~original Luwrain distribution is~provided as~a~stand-alone [local:/download/distr/ bootable ISO-image]
for~using completely free~of~charge and capable of~installation without any sighted help.

All~of~that makes Luwrain a~solution which could be~suitable for~doing most~of~popular tasks 
for~various groups of~users.
Experienced users, perhaps, could find it~better than usual screen readers because 
Luwrain let doing some tasks more quickly and more~comfortable.
Inexperienced users, including seniors,  get~access to~information technologies 
without  long  prior learning; 
at~most they should to~pass through a~short system guide
offered on~launch of~Luwrain LiveCD.

We~take  these benefits as~quite sufficient to~do our work 
but returning to~Luwrain portability it is~possible to~discover new areas previously  left mostly untouched.
Luwrain can be~used as~[local:/doc/new-app/ a~framework for~creating  the~applications] 
designed specially for~blind people.
Luwrain promises that these applications will be~understandable for~disabled persons 
and available for~them due to~presence of~Java on~most of~popular platforms.
Meantime, authors of~applications for~Luwrain may know nothing 
about assistive technologies, 
they should just take a~set of~Luwrain classes.

